      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Leafs' faithful are trapped in a nightmare loop&mdash;another gut-wrenching playoff loss, the kind that turns Scotiabank Arena into a tomb.<strong>Ottawa Senators snuffed out Toronto's flicker of hope last night, 3-1, in Game 2 of this first-round bloodbath</strong>, leaving the series at 0-2 with the Atlantic's eighth-place squad, 32-36-14 and 78 points, staring down a 35-game deficit to relevance. The power play, that supposed savior, went ice-cold again&mdash;zero goals on four chances&mdash;while the Senators' Tim St&uuml;tzle danced through defenders like they were pylons, burying the dagger in the third. Goaltending? Woll stood tall with 28 saves, but the forwards mustered just 23 shots, a feeble echo of their 112-point regular-season tease. Captain Tavares, nursing that nagging upper-body tweak from Game 1, logged 18 shifts but couldn't spark the fire; Marner flashed moments, yet the streak hits L7 now, four straight playoff heartbreaks. This isn't rebuilding&mdash;it's reckoning. <strong>Game 3 thunders into Ottawa Saturday night; win there, or the golf courses beckon early, and 20 years without a Cup final grows to 21.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated April 16, 2026"
      },
