    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "7-10",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays' early-season buzz fizzled into frustration last night in Milwaukee, where a <strong>1-2 gut-punch loss to the Brewers</strong> snapped their mini-resurgence and left them grasping at 7-10, fourth in the AL East, 3 games back with a playoff seed mocking them at 12th. Dylan Cease carved through five scoreless innings on April 15, but two fluky runs in the eighth undid it all&mdash;Abner Uribe slamming the door for Milwaukee's homestand salvation&mdash;after they'd clawed a 7&ndash;10 thriller the night before on Daulton Varsho's third bomb and Vladimir Guerrero Jr.'s never-quit double. No major injuries biting yet, but the lineup's inconsistency stings; Varsho and Andr&eacute;s Gim&eacute;nez flashed pop in the series, yet the bats went quiet when it mattered most. At 7-10, this isn't contender fire&mdash;it's a sober wake-up, trajectory dipping with that one-game skid. <strong>Today's noon rubber match at the Brewers</strong> decides if they steal a split or slink home buried deeper&mdash;win it, and momentum flickers; fold, and the AL East vultures circle closer.",
        "updated": "Updated April 16, 2026"
      },
